title: Aust shares get off to firm start
text:
Wed, Sep 16, 2015, 1:05 PM AEST - Australia Markets close in 2 hrs 55 mins Aust shares get off to firm start AAP – 2 hours 8 minutes ago Recommend 
The Australian share market has got off to a positive start after strong leads from wall Street, but traders remain wary ahead of a Federal Reserve rate decision later this week. 
The Dow Jones Industrial Average closed up 1.40 per cent, after modestly higher US retail sales. 
However, US bond yields rose to four-and-half year highs, suggesting investors are ready for the Fed to finally act on its key interest rate after months of talking about it. 
"The markets remain volatile. Investors don't want to hold big positions ahead of Friday's (AEST) decision (by the Fed), so I wouldn't be surprised if we give up some of the gains before close," said Chris Conway, head of research and trading at Australian Stock Report. 
Investors had stayed away from mid-caps, and the focus would remain on frontline bank, energy and mining stocks, he said. 
The major banks were trading higher on Wednesday, with National Australia Bank gaining 42 cents at $30.25, Westpac up 44 cents at $30.64, ANZ rising 37 cents to $27.51, and Commonwealth Bank adding $1.4 to $74.82. 
Energy and resources stocks also recovered some ground. 
BHP Billiton rose 55 cents to $23.90, rival Rio Tinto gained 80 cents to $51.54, and Fortescue Mining added 4.0 cents to $2.05. Energy producer Santos was up 12 cents to $4.77, and bid target Oil Search gained 8.0 cents to $7.35. 
Seek shares were down 1.0 cent at $11.73, while Flight Centre lost 62 cents to $35.67, with both stocks turning ex-dividend on Wednesday. 
KEY FACTS 
* At 1034 AEST on Wednesday, the benchmark S&P/ASX200 index was up 61.7 points, or 1.23 per cent, at 5,080.1 points. 
* The broader All Ordinaries index was up 58.5 points, or 1.16 per cent, at 5,105.11 points. 
* September share price index futures contract was up 80 points at 5,086 points, with 60,600 contracts traded.
